Let the roots of the quadratic equation $x^2 + bx + c = 0$ be $r_1$ and $r_2$. It is well known that the sum of the roots is equal to $-b$ and the product of the roots is equal to $c$.
Thus, $$r_1 + r_2 = -b, \quad r_1 \cdot r_2 = c.$$The difference of the roots is $|r_1 - r_2| = |b - 2c|$. Thus, $$|r_1 - r_2| = |r_1 + r_2||\frac{r_1}{r_1+r_2}-\frac{r_2}{r_1+r_2}|=|(-b)||\frac{r_1}{-b}-\frac{r_2}{-b}|=|-b|\left|\frac{c}{-b}-\frac{c}{-b}\right| = |b-2c|.$$Hence, $$|-b||\frac{c}{-b}-\frac{c}{-b}| = |b-2c| \Rightarrow |-b|\left|\frac{c}{b} - 1\right| = |b-2c|.$$Now, we can simplify and solve for $c$: \begin{align*} |-b|\left|\frac{c}{b} - 1\right| &= |b-2c|\\ \Rightarrow\quad |-b|&=|-c + c|-b| = |b-2c|\\ \Rightarrow\quad c &= 2c\\ \Rightarrow\qquad\ c &= \boxed{\frac{b}{2}} \quad \text{(taking the positive solution, since c must be positive)} \end{align*} Thus, we found the answer: c is $\frac{b}{2}$. \end{document} 
